t in the Nordic countries, and capital of the V\u00e4stra G\u00f6taland County. It is situated by Kattegat, on the west coast of Sweden, and has a population of approximately 570,000 in the city center and about 1 million inhabitants in the metropolitan area.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Gothenburg was founded as a heavily fortified, primarily Dutch, trading colony, by royal charter in 1621 by King Gustavus Adolphus. In addition to the generous privileges (e.g. tax relaxation) given to his Dutch allies from the then-ongoing Thirty Years' War, the king also attracted significant numbers of his German and Scottish allies to populate his only town on the western coast. At a key strategic location at the mouth of the G\u00f6ta \u00e4lv, where Scandinavia's largest drainage basin enters the sea, the Port of Gothenburg is now the largest port in the Nordic countries.", "qas": [{"question": "who founded the dutch trading colony ?", "answers": [], "id": "(33, 1, 0)"}]}, {"context": "Gothenburg is home to many students, as the city includes the University of Gothenburg and Chalmers University of Technology. Volvo was founded in Gothenburg in 1927. The original parent Volvo Group and the now separate Volvo Car Corporation are still headquartered on the island of Hisingen in the city. Other key companies are SKF and Astra Zeneca.", "qas": [{"question": "what is the name of the university of technology university ?", "answers": [], "id": "(33, 2, 0)"}]}, {"context": "Gothenburg is served by G\u00f6teborg Landvetter Airport southeast of the city center. The smaller G\u00f6teborg City Airport, from the city center, was closed to regular airline traffic in 2015.", "qas": [{"question": "what is the airport in the city center ?", "answers": [], "id": "(33, 3, 0)"}]}, {"context": "The city hosts the Gothia Cup, the world's largest youth football tournament, alongside some of the largest annual events in Scandinavia. The Gothenburg Film Festival, held in January since 1979, is the leadi